            <p>
              <m>f(x)+3, f(x)-3, f(x+3)</m>, and <m>f(x-3)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>2f(x), \frac{1}{2}f(x), f(2x)</m>,
              and <m>f\left(\frac{1}{2} x\right)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>-f(x)</m> and <m>f(-x)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="sec_symmetry">
    <title>Symmetry</title>
    <p>
      Some graphs do not change under certain transformations.
      For example,
      the graph of <m>f(x) = x^2</m> shown in <xref ref="fig_taalmanpage66a" /> below remains the same if we reflect it across the <m>y</m>-axis.
      We say that this function has <em><m>y</m>-axis reflectional symmetry</em>.
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="fig_taalmanpage66a">
      <caption><m>y=x^2</m> is preserved under reflection across the <m>y</m>-axis.</caption>
      <image width="80%" source="TaalmanPage66a.png"/>
    </figure>
    <p>
      As another example, the graph of
      <m>g(x) = x^3</m> shown in <xref ref="fig_taalmanpage66b" /> below remains the same if we reflect it first across the <m>y</m>-axis and then across the <m>x</m>-axis.
      This double-reflection across the <m>x</m>- and <m>y</m>-axis is equivalent to rotation around the origin by <m>180^\circ</m>.
      Take a moment to experiment with this:
      on a piece of scrap paper, draw a smiley face or some other picture.
      Flip the paper vertically and then horizontally
      (or horizontally and then vertically).
      This gives you the same result as rotating the paper by 180 degrees.
      A function that is preserved under the transformation of
      <m>180^\circ</m> rotation is said to have <m>180^\circ</m>
      <em>rotational symmetry</em>.
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="fig_taalmanpage66b">
      <caption><m>y=x^3</m> is preserved under <m>180^\circ</m> rotation about the origin.</caption>
      <image width="80%" source="TaalmanPage66b.png"/>
    </figure>
    <p>
      These types of symmetries are also called <em>even symmetry</em>
      and <em>odd symmetry</em>,
      since power functions with even powers all have <m>y</m>-axis symmetry and power functions with odd powers all have rotational symmetry. Let's try to understand algebraically what makes the graph of a function <m>f</m> have even or odd symmetry. The graph has even symmetry when the following equivalence holds: 
      <me>
        (x,y) \text{ is on the graph of } f \iff (-x,y) \text{ is on the graph of } f
      </me>.
      Since a point <m>(x,y)</m> is on the graph of <m>f</m> if and only if <m>x</m> is in the domain of <m>f</m> and <m>f(x)=y</m>, we see that the above equivalence is equivalent to the algebraic statement 
      <me>
        f(-x)=f(x)
      </me>
      for all <m>x</m> in the domain of <m>f</m>. Similarly, the graph of <m>f</m> has odd symmetry if and only if <m>f(x)=-f(x)</m> for all <m>x</m> in its domain. This is the motivation for the following definition and table. 
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="d_even_odd">
      <title>Even and odd functions</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>f</m> be a function whose domain <m>D</m> satisfies the following property: if <m>x\in D</m>, then <m>-x\in D</m>. 
          <ul>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>f</m> is <term>even</term> if 
                <men xml:id="eq_even">
            f(-x)=f(x)
          </men>
          for all <m>x\in D</m>. 
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>f</m> is <term>odd</term> if 
                <men xml:id="eq_odd">
            f(-x)=-f(x)
          </men>
          for all <m>x\in D</m>. 
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul> 
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <table xml:id="table_even_odd">
      <title>Even and odd symmetry</title>
      <tabular>
        <row header="yes" bottom="medium">
          <cell>Symmetry name</cell>
          <cell>Alg. definition</cell>
          <cell>Graphical symmetry</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>Even</cell><cell><m>f(-x)=f(x)</m></cell><cell><m>y</m>-axis reflectional symmetry</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>Odd</cell><cell><m>f(-x)=-f(x)</m></cell><cell><m>180^\circ</m> rotational symmetry</cell>
        </row>
      </tabular>
    </table>
    <remark>
      <title>Even/odd: domain</title>
      <p>
        Observe the technical restriction placed on the domain of a function in <xref ref="d_even_odd"/>. Namely, we do not even ask whether a function <m>f\colon D\rightarrow \R</m> is even or odd, if its domain <m>D</m> does not satisfy the property
        <me>
          x\in D\implies -x\in D
        </me>.
        For example, <m>n</m>-th root functions <m>f(x)=\sqrt[n]{x}</m> for <m>n</m> even are not possible candidates for evenness or oddness, since their domain <m>D=[0,\infty)</m> does not satisfy this property: <eg/>, <m>1\in D</m>, but <m>-1\notin D</m>.
      </p>
    </remark>
    <example xml:id="eg_even_odd">
    <title>Even/odd power functions</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>f(x)=x^n</m>, where <m>n\ne 0</m> is a nonzero integer. Show that <m>f</m> is even if <m>n</m> is even, and odd if <m>n</m> is odd. 
    </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
    <p>
    First consider the case where <m>n=2k</m> is even. For any <m>x</m> in the domain of <m>f</m>, we have 
    <md>
      <mrow>f(-x) \amp = (-x)^{2k}</mrow>
      <mrow> \amp =((-1)x)^{2k}</mrow>
      <mrow> \amp =(-1)^{2k}x^{2k} \amp (\text{common exp.})</mrow>
      <mrow> \amp =x^{2k} \amp ((-1)^{2k}=1)</mrow>
      <mrow> \amp =f(x)</mrow>
    </md>.
    Thus <m>f</m> is even in this case, as claimed. 
    </p>
    <p>
      Now assume <m>n=2k+1</m> is odd. Now we have 
      <md>
      <mrow>f(-x) \amp = (-x)^{2k+1}</mrow>
      <mrow> \amp =((-1)x)^{2k+1}</mrow>
      <mrow> \amp =(-1)^{2k}x^{2k+1} \amp (\text{common exp.})</mrow>
      <mrow> \amp =-x^{2k+1} \amp ((-1)^{2k+1}=-1)</mrow>
      <mrow> \amp =-f(x)</mrow>
    </md>
    for all <m>x</m>, showing <m>f</m> to be odd. 
    </p>
    </solution>
    </example>
    <p>
      It should be noted that being even or odd is a special property not enjoyed by all functions. In fact, chances are, if you write down a random algebraic function, it will be neither even nor odd.
    </p>
    <p>
      The argument used to show that a function is not even (or not odd), is qualitatively very different than for showing the function is even (or is odd). Namely, to show the property in question does <em>not</em> hold, it suffices to find a single explicit counterexample. The next example illustrates this. 
    </p>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Show that the function 
          <m>f(x) = x^2+x</m> is neither even nor odd.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          First observe that the implied domain of <m>h</m> is <m>\R</m>, since <m>f</m> is a polynomial.
          To show <m>f</m> is not even, it suffices to show that <m>f(-x)\ne f(x)</m> for <em>some</em> element <m>x\in \R </m>. This is easy: we have 
          <md>
            <mrow>f(1) \amp = 2</mrow>
            <mrow>f(-1) \amp = (-1)^2+(-1)=0</mrow>
          </md>, 
          and thus <m>f(1)\ne f(-1)</m>. We conclude that <m>h</m> is not even. 
        </p>
        <p>
          Similarly, to show <m>f</m> is not odd, we need only find an iput <m>x</m> satisfying <m>f(-x)\ne -f(x)</m>. The same input <m>x=1</m> works in this case as well, since 
          <m>f(-1)\ne -f(1) </m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Sketch a graph that has neither <m>y</m>-axis symmetry nor <m>180^\circ</m> rotational symmetry.
          Congratulations!
          You have drawn the graph of a function that is neither even nor odd.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <p>
      <xref ref="eg_even_odd"/> illustrates the important role played by the <q>for all</q> quantifier in <xref ref="d_even_odd"/>. A function is even (or odd) if it satisfies the relevant equation <em>for all</em> elements in its domain; and it is not even (or not odd) if it fails to satisfy the relevant equation <em>for some</em> element in its domain. In essence, being even or odd is a function equality statement involving the two functions <m>f(x)</m> and <m>g(x)=f(-x)</m>: <m>f</m> is even if <m>f=g</m> (as functions); and <m>f</m> is odd if <m>f=-g</m> (as functions). (See <xref ref="d_function_equality"/>.) 
    </p>
    <p>
      Consider the example <m>f(x)=x^2+x</m> again. In deciding whether <m>f</m> is even or odd, we really are comparing it with the function 
      <me>
        g(x)=f(-x)=(-x)^2+(-x)=x^2-x
      </me>.
      Comparing the formulas for <m>f</m> and <m>g</m>, it seems clear that these two functions are not equal, and hence that <m>f</m> is not even. But we need to be careful here! As we have seen before, different formulas can sometimes be seen to define the same function after some algebra. The surefire way of showing two functions are not equal is find a single instance of an input where their outputs differ. This is exactly what we did in the solution to <xref ref="eg_even_odd"/>. 
    </p>
    <p>
      In this particular case, however, we are aided by the fact that all the functions involved are <em>polynomials</em>, and that polynomial equality is equivalent to having like coefficients. (See <xref ref="cor_poly_equality"/>.) That is, we can immediately see that the three functions 
      <md>
        <mrow>f(x) \amp =x^2+x</mrow>
        <mrow>g(x) \amp =x^2-x</mrow>
        <mrow>-g(x) \amp =-x^2+x</mrow>
      </md>
      are distinct simply by comparing their coefficients. It follows that <m>f</m> is not even (since <m>f(-x)\ne f(x)</m>) and <m>f</m> is not odd (since <m>-f(-x)\ne f(x)</m>). 
    </p>
    <p>
      Of course, not all functions are polynomials, and so things are not always this straightforward. When in doubt, to definitely show a function is not even (or not odd), provide an explicit counterexample. 
    </p>
    <example xml:id="eg_even_odd_neither">
      <title>Even/odd/neither</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Determine algebraically whether the given function is even, odd,
          or neither. Confirm your answer graphically using <xref ref="fig_even_odd_neither"/>. 
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>f(x) = \frac{1}{x}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>g(x) = x^4-x^2</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>h(x) = \frac{2+x}{1+x^2}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="fig_even_odd_neither">
          <caption>Graphs of example functions</caption>
          <sidebyside>
            <figure xml:id="fig_eg_even">
              <caption><m>f(x)=\tfrac{1}{x}</m></caption>
              <image>
                <sageplot>
              f(x)=1/x
              plot(f(x),(x,-5,5), ymin=-5, ymax=5, color='blue')
              </sageplot>
            </image>
            </figure>
            <figure xml:id="fig_eg_odd">
              <caption><m>g(x)=x^4-x^2</m></caption>
              <image><sageplot>
              g(x)=x^4-x^2
              plot(g(x),(x,-2,2), ymin=-1, ymax=3, color='blue')
              </sageplot></image>
            </figure>
            <figure xml:id="fig_eg_neither">
              <caption><m>h(x)=\frac{2+x}{1+x^2}</m></caption>
              <image>
                <shortdescription>Sageplot of function h</shortdescription>
              <sageplot>
              h(x)=(2+x)/(1+x^2)
              plot(h(x),(x,-5,5), ymin=-1, ymax=3, color='blue')
              </sageplot>
              </image>
            </figure>
          </sidebyside>
        </figure>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We first determine algebraically whether each function satisfies the definition of even or odd
          (or if it does not)
          and then verify graphically.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                First observe that the domain of <m>f</m> is <m>D=\R-\{0\}</m>. 
                Since
                <me>
                  f(-x) = \frac{1}{-x} = -\frac{1}{x}  = -f(x)
                </me>
                for all <m>x\in D</m>, we see that <m>f</m> is odd. Looking at the formulas, it seems clear that <m>f(-x)\ne f(x)</m> for all <m>x\in D</m>, and hence that <m>f</m> is not even. To be sure, however, we provide a counterexample: we have <m>f(1)=1/1=1</m> and <m>f(-1)=1/(-1)=-1</m>. Since <m>f(1)\ne f(-1)</m>, we conclude that <m>f</m> is not even. 
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                In this case the implied domain of <m>g</m> is <m>\R</m>. Since 
                <me>
                  g(-x) = (-x)^4-(-x)^2  = x^4-x^2 = g(x)
                </me>
                for all <m>x\in \R</m>, we conclude that <m>g</m> is even. 
              </p>
              <p>
                Is <m>g</m> odd? In this case since <m>g(x)=x^4-x^2</m> and <m>-g(-x)=-x^4+x^2</m> are both polynomials, we see that the two functions are not equal simply by comparing coefficients. Thus <m>g</m> is not odd.  
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
               The implied domain of <m>h</m> is <m>\R</m>, since <m>1+x^2\ne 0</m> for all <m>x\in \R</m>. We have 
                <me>
                  h(-x) = \frac{2+(-x)}{1+(-x)^2} = \frac{2-x}{1+x^2}
                </me>
                for all <m>x\in \R</m>. 
                Looking just at the formulas, it seems that the function <m>h(-x)</m> is equal neither to <m>h(x)</m> nor <m>-h(x)</m>. To be sure, however, we provide explicit counterexamples to both evenness and oddness. 
              </p>
              <p>
                Note that <m>h(1)=3/2</m> and <m>h(-1)=1/2</m>. Since <m>h(1)\ne h(-1)</m>, we conclude that <m>h</m> is not even. Furthermore, since <m>h(1)\ne -h(-1)</m>, we conclude that <m>h</m> is not odd. 
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        Looking at the graphs of <m>f</m>,  <m>g</m>, and <m>h</m>, in <xref ref="fig_even_odd_neither"/>, we can confirm our conclusions above immediately: the graph of <m>f</m> exhibits <m>180^\circ</m> rotational symmetry, but not <m>y</m>-axis reflectional symmetry; the graph of <m>g</m> exhibits <m>y</m>-axis reflectional symmetry, but not <m>180^\circ</m> rotational symmetry; and the graph of <m>h</m> exhibits neither type of symmetry.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Vertex form of a quadratic function</title>
    <p>
      Recall that every quadratic function <m>g(x)=ax^2+bx+c</m> can be expressed in <em>vertex</em> form as <m>g(x)=a(x+d)^2+e</m> for some constants <m>d</m> and <m>e</m>. This result, along with our newfound understanding of function transformations, allows us to relate the graph of <m>g(x)=a(x+d)^2+e</m> to the graph of the simple power function <m>f(x)=x^2</m>. Indeed, applying the sequence of transformations 
      <me>
        f(x)\xmapsto{\text{horiz. shift}} f(x+d)\xmapsto{\text{vert. scale}}af(x+d)\xmapsto{\text{vert. shift}}af(x+d)+e
      </me>
      yields the sequence of functions 
      <me>
        f(x)=x^2\mapsto p(x)=(x+d)^2\mapsto q(x)=a(x+d)^2\mapsto g(x)=a(x+d)^2+e
      </me>.
      As a result, the graph of an arbitrary quadratic function can be obtained from the graph of <m>f(x)=x^2</m> by performing a horizontal shift, followed by a vertical scaling, followed by a vertical shift. <xref ref="fig_vertex_form"/> illustrates this process for the function <m>g(x)=-2(x-1)+3</m>.
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="fig_vertex_form">
      <caption>Transformations and vertex form</caption>
      <sbsgroup widths="43% 43%">
        <sidebyside>
          <figure xml:id="vertex_form_orig">
            <caption><m>f(x)=x^2</m></caption>
            <image>
              <shortdescription>Graph of x squared</shortdescription>
              <sageplot>
              f(x)=x^2
              plot(f(x),(x,-3,3), ymin=-1, ymax=9, color='blue')
              </sageplot>
            </image>
          </figure>
          <figure xml:id="vertex_form_second">
            <caption><m>p(x)=(x-1)^2</m></caption>
            <image>
              <shortdescription>Shift original function</shortdescription>
              <sageplot>
              p(x)=(x-1)^2
              plot(p(x),(x,-2,4), ymin=-1, ymax=9, color='blue')
              </sageplot>
            </image>
          </figure>
        </sidebyside>
        <sidebyside>
          <figure xml:id="vertex_form_third">
            <caption><m>q(x)=-2(x-1)^2</m></caption>
            <image>
              <shortdescription>Scaling the shift</shortdescription>
              <sageplot>
              f(x)=-2*(x-1)^2
              plot(f(x),(x,-2,4), ymin=-20, ymax=2, color='blue')
              </sageplot>
            </image>
          </figure>
          <figure xml:id="vertex_form_last">
            <caption><m>g(x)=-2(x-1)^2+3</m></caption>
            <image>
              <shortdescription>The final function</shortdescription>
              <sageplot>
              p(x)=-2*(x-1)^2+3
              plot(p(x),(x,-2,4), ymin=-20, ymax=5, color='blue')
              </sageplot>
            </image>
          </figure>
        </sidebyside>
      </sbsgroup>
    </figure>
    <theorem xml:id="th_vertex_form">
    <title>Vertex form</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>f(x)=a(x-b)^2+c</m>, where <m>a\ne 0</m>. The graph of <m>f</m> is a parabola with vertex at the point 
    <me>
      (b,f(b))=(b,c)
    </me>.
    The graph of <m>f</m> extends upwards if <m>a&gt; 0</m> and downwards if <m>a&lt; 0</m>. 
    </p>
    </statement>
    </theorem>
    
    <example>
      <statement>
       <p>
        Compute the vertex form for the given quadratic function <m>f</m>, then provide a graph of <m>f</m>. 
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>f(x)=-2x^2-8x-5</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>f(x)=48x^2-72x+27</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
       </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                The vertex form of <m>f</m> is computed as 
                <md>
                  <mrow>f(x) \amp = -2(x^2+4)-5</mrow>
                  <mrow> \amp = -2((x+2)^2-4)-5</mrow>
                  <mrow> \amp = -2(x+2)^2+3</mrow>
                </md>.
                The graph of <m>f</m> is a downward-oriented parabola with vertex at <m>(-2,3)</m>. 
                
              </p>
               <image xml:id="im_vertex_form1" width="50%">
                  <shortdescription>Graph of a parabola</shortdescription>
                  <sageplot>
                  f(x)=-2*(x+2)^2+3
                  plot(f(x),x,-5,1)
                  </sageplot>
                </image>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The vertex form of <m>f</m> is computed as 
                <md>
                  <mrow>f(x) \amp = 48(x^2-\tfrac{3}{2}x)+27</mrow>
                  <mrow> \amp =48((x-\tfrac{3}{4})^2-\tfrac{9}{16})+27</mrow>
                  <mrow> \amp =48(x-\tfrac{3}{4})^2</mrow>
                </md>.
                The graph of <m>f</m> is an upward-oriented parabola with vertex at <m>(3/4,0)</m>. 
                
              </p>
               <image xml:id="im_vertex_form2" width="50%">
                  <shortdescription>Graph of a parabola</shortdescription>
                  <sageplot>
                  f(x)=48*x^2-72*x+27
                  plot(f(x),x,-1,2)
                  </sageplot>
                </image>
            </li>

          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
